      "name": "Simple Memory"
    },
    {
      "parameters": {
        "content": "## Feature & Bug Automator\n### Problem\nIn many software projects, requirements from business teams or product owners arrive in natural language and are often unstructured. They have to be translated by hand into user stories, subtasks and acceptance criteria, which is time-consuming and frequently leads to misunderstandings. The process is error-prone and slows down collaboration between the business side and the development team.\n\n### Solution\nThis workflow automatically turns unstructured requirements and reports into clearly structured agile artifacts.\nIt detects whether the input is a feature request or a bug report and creates the matching Jira tickets:\n\n- for feature requests it generates a user story, subtasks and acceptance criteria,\n\n- for bug reports it generates a description, steps to reproduce, expected and actual behavior, and a priority.\n\n- Through RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation) the AI agent can additionally draw on specific knowledge about the product and internal team processes, making the results more context-aware and practical.\n\n- The results are returned as structured JSON and can be imported into Jira automatically.\n\n### Phases\n#### Phase 1 - Core functionality\n#### Phase 2 - Bug handling and prioritization\n#### Phase 3 - Knowledge integration with RAG\n\n---\nBuilt by Majd Edriss - software, automation, AI integration - me-dev.de",
        "height": 880,
        "width": 464
      },
      "type": "n8n-nodes-base.stickyNote",
      "typeVersion": 1,
      "position": [
        13360,
        5536
      ],
      "id": "da2c504a-3d55-4968-9b13-755cabfe4934",
      "name": "Sticky Note"
    },
    {
      "parameters": {
        "inputText": "=Determine whether the following text is a feature request or a bug report.\nRespond only in valid JSON:\n{ \"type\": \"feature\" | \"bug\" | \"unclear\" }\n\nText: {{ $json.Text }}",
        "categories": {
          "categories": [
            {
              "category": "feature"
            },
            {
              "category": "bug"
            },
            {
              "category": "unclear"
            }
          ]
        },
        "options": {}
      },
      "type": "@n8n/n8n-nodes-langchain.textClassifier",
      "typeVersion": 1.1,
      "position": [
        14112,
        6080
      ],
      "id": "39215845-aa77-4842-a51d-16106633595c",
      "name": "Text Classifier",
      "executeOnce": false
    },
    {
      "parameters": {
        "promptType": "define",
        "text": "=Input: {{ $json.Text }}",
        "hasOutputParser": true,
        "options": {
          "systemMessage": "=You are an experienced requirements engineer.\nYour task is to turn a bug report written in natural language into a clean Scrum bug report.\n\nYou have access to a tool that retrieves data from a semantic vector database.\n\nAlways query the vector database first.\n\nIf relevant data is found:\n- Base your answer only on that data.\n- Provide the source(s) from the knowledge base (\"source\": \"quote\"), not as a blob.\n\nIf no relevant data is found:\n- Return the source as an empty string (\"source\": \"\").\n\nRules:\n- Respond only in valid JSON (no comments, no explanations).\n- Use clear everyday language, no jargon or developer terms.\n- No tests, no UI mockups, no code references, no explanations.\n- summary: a short description of the bug, max 100 characters.\n\nExample: if the current version number is requested, output it as a number, not as the text \"current version number\"."
        }
      },
      "id": "cbc41a69-9705-4f29-b91c-5204c2393eac",
